e enumerated as follows:\n<ref name=\"Pitlocal.org\">[http://webcache.googleusercontent.com/search?q=cache:GX9UMhZNdisJ:www.pitloklocal.org/songko47.xls+%E0%B9%82%E0%B8%81%E0%B8%A3%E0%B8%87%E0%B9%80%E0%B8%81%E0%B8%A3%E0%B8%87&hl=en&ct=clnk&cd=7&gl=us Tha Tan at Pitlocal.org] (Thai){{DL|date=April 2020}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n| No.\n| English\n| Thai\n|-\n| 1\n| Ban Bang Phi\n| \u0e1a\u0e49\u0e32\u0e19\u0e1a\u0e32\u0e07\u0e1c\u0e35\n|-\n| 2-3{{efn|A village with two mubans.<ref>[http://phitsanulok.kapook.com/%E0%B8%9A%E0%B8%B2%E0%B8%87%E0%B8%81%E0%B8%A3%E0%B8%B0%E0%B8%97%E0%B8%B8%E0%B9%88%E0%B8%A1/%E0%B8%97%E0%B9%88%E0%B8%B2%E0%B8%95%E0%B8%B2%E0%B8%A5 \u0e15\u0e33\u0e1a\u0e25\u0e17\u0e48\u0e32\u0e15\u0e32\u0e25 \u0e2d\u0e33\u0e40\u0e20\u0e2d\u0e1a\u0e32\u0e07\u0e01\u0e23\u0e30\u0e17\u0e38\u0e48\u0e21 \u0e08\u0e31\u0e07\u0e2b\u0e27\u0e31\u0e14\u0e1e\u0e34\u0e29\u0e13\u0e38\u0e42\u0e25\u0e01 - \u0e28\u0e39\u0e19\u0e22\u0e4c\u0e02\u0e49\u0e2d\u0e21\u0e39\u0e25\u0e1b\u0e23\u0e30\u0e40\u0e17\u0e28\u0e44\u0e17\u0e22 - Thailand Information Center] {{in lang|th}}</ref>}}\n| Ban Tha Tan\n| \u0e1a\u0e49\u0e32\u0e19\u0e17\u0e48\u0e32\u0e15\u0e32\u0e25\n|-\n| 4\n| Ban Boo Yai\n| \u0e1a\u0e49\u0e32\u0e19\u0e1a\u0e38\u0e43\u0e2b\u0e0d\u0e48\n|-\n| 5\n| Ban Wangsan\n| \u0e1a\u0e49\u0e32\u0e19\u0e27\u0e31\u0e07\u0e2a\u0e32\u0e23\n|-\n| 6\n| Ban Tha Dindaeng\n| \u0e1a\u0e49\u0e32\u0e19\u0e17\u0e48\u0e32\u0e14\u0e34\u0e19\u0e41\u0e14\u0e07\n|-\n| 7\n| Ban Nern Sa'at\n| \u0e1a\u0e49\u0e32\u0e19\u0e40\u0e19\u0e34\u0e19\u0e2a\u0e30\u0e2d\u0e32\u0e14\n|-\n| 8\n| Ban Thung Noi\n| \u0e1a\u0e49\u0e32\u0e19\u0e17\u0e38\u0e48\u0e07\u0e19\u0e49\u0e2d\u0e22\n|-\n| 9\n| Ban Gai Rawa\n| \u0e1a\u0e49\u0e32\u0e19\u0e44\u0e01\u0e48\u0e23\u0e30\u0e27\u0e49\u0e32\n|}\n\n==Temples==\nTha Tan is home to the following eight temples:<ref name=\"WebWat.com\">[http://www.webwat.net/temple_detail.php?province_id=9&region_id=1&page=5 Tha Tan on WebWat.com] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070903091123/http://www.webwat.net/temple_detail.php?province_id=9&region_id=1&page=5 |date=2007-09-03 }}</ref>\n*Wat Pak Khlong (Thai:  \u0e27\u0e31\u0e14\u0e1b\u0e32\u0e01\u0e04\u0e25\u0e2d\u0e07, Temple of the Mouth of the Canal) in Ban Tha Dindaeng\n*Wat Tha Tan (Thai:  \u0e27\u0e31\u0e14\u0e17\u0e48\u0e32\u0e15\u0e32\u0e25) in Ban Tha Tan\n*Wat Tan Phlong (Thai:  \u0e27\u0e31\u0e14\u0e15\u0e32\u0e25\u0e42\u0e1e\u0e25\u0e07, Bright Sugar-Palm Temple) in Ban Boo Yai\n*\u0e27\u0e31\u0e14\u0e21\u0e07\u0e04\u0e25\u0e1e\u0e38\u0e17\u0e18\u0e32\u0e23\u0e32\u0e21 in Ban Wangsan\n*Wat Wangsan (Thai:  \u0e27\u0e31\u0e14\u0e27\u0e31\u0e07\u0e2a\u0e32\u0e23) in Ban Wangsan\n*Wat Luang (Thai:  \u0e27\u0e31\u0e14\u0e2b\u0e25\u0e27\u0e07) in Ban Bang Phi\n*Wat Thung Noi (Thai:  \u0e27\u0e31\u0e14\u0e17\u0e38\u0e48\u0e07\u0e19\u0e49\u0e2d\u0e22) in Ban Tung Noi\n*Wat Nern Sa'at (Thai:  \u0e27\u0e31\u0e14\u0e40\u0e19\u0e34\u0e19\u0e2a\u0e30\u0e2d\u0e32\u0e14) in Ban Nern Sa'at\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Tambon of Phitsanulok Province]]\n[[Category:Populated places in Phitsanulok Province]]\n", "name_user": "Seligne", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tha_Tan"}
{"title_page": "Jane Somerville", "text_new": "{{short description|British physician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{EngvarB|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox medical person\n| honorific_prefix  = \n| name              = Jane Somerville\n| honorific_suffix  = \n| image             = Jane Somerville, library.jpg\n| image_size        = \n| alt               = \n| caption           = Jane Somerville in her personal library (2019)\n| birth_name        = Jane Platnauer\n| birth_date        = {{birth date and age|df=y|24 January 1933}}\n| birth_place       = \n| death_date        = <!-- {{Death date and age|df=y|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date)  -->\n| death_place       = \n| death_cause       = \n| nationality       = British\n| citizenship       = \n| education         = *[[Queen's College, London]]\n*[[King's College London GKT School of Medical Education|Guy's Hospital Medical School]] \n| occupation        = \n| years_active      = \n| known_for         = *Physician to Britain's first [[heart transplantation]] (1968)\n*Founding concept of [[GUCH]]\n*Idea of the first World Congress of Paediatric Cardiology\n*Founding the charity \"The Somerville Foundation\"\n| relations         = \n| website           = \n| profession        = Physician\n| field             = [[Cardiology]]\n| work_institutions = *[[University College Hospital at Westmoreland Street|National Heart Hospital]] \n*[[Great Ormond Street Hospital|Hospital for Sick Children in Great Ormond Street]]\n*[[Brompton Hospital]]\n*[[Imperial College]]\n| specialism        = [[Congenital heart defects]]\n| research_field    = \n| notable_works     = \n| prizes            = *Gold Medal of the [[European Society of Cardiology]]\n* Distinguished Service Award of the [[American College of Cardiology]]\n| child             = \n| module2           = \n| signature         = \n}}\n'''Jane Somerville''' (n\u00e9e '''Platnauer'''; 24 January 1933) is a British emeritus professor of [[cardiologist|cardiology]], [[Imperial College]], who is best known for defining the concept and subspecialty of [[GUCH|grown ups with congenital heart disease]] (GUCH) and being chosen as the physician involved with Britain's first [[heart transplantation]] in 1968.\n\nSomerville was educated first at a boys preparatory school in North Wales, then [[Queen's College, London]], and later at [[King's College London GKT School of Medical Education|Guy's Hospital Medical School]]. Initially drawn to surgery, she chose to pursue a career in cardiology at the [[University College Hospital at Westmoreland Street|National Heart Hospital]], [[Great Ormond Street Hospital|Hospital for Sick Children in Great Ormond Street]] and later at the [[Brompton Hospital]].\n\nHer work led to the opening of the world's first dedicated ward for children and adolescents with congenital heart disease, the first World Congress of Paediatric Cardiology in London, and a GUCH charity which was later renamed \"The Somerville Foundation\" in her honour. The medical professionals who she trained and who have come to celebrate and follow her are known as \"Unicorns\".\n\n==Early life and education==\nJane Somerville was born in [[Edwardes Square]], [[Kensington]], London,<ref name=Anderson2010/> on 24 January 1933<ref name=Warness2008>{{Cite journal|last=Warnes|first=Carole A.|date=April 2008|title=Jane Somerville|journal=Clinical Cardiology|volume=31|issue=4|pages=183\u2013184|doi=10.1002/clc.20279|pmid=18404729|pmc=6652976}}</ref> to Joseph Bertram Platnauer, who was a theatre critic for the ''[[Tatler]]'' magazine<ref name=Anderson2010/> and Pearl Ashton who worked on ''[[Vogue (British magazine)|Vogue]]''.<ref name=Warness2008/><ref name=Birthday>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/happy-birthday-professor-jane-somerville-80-zfc7m3pz5pb|title=Happy Birthday: Professor Jane Somerville, 80|date=24 January 2013|work=The Times|access-date=4 March 2019|issn=0140-0460}}</ref> Her early childhood was spent under the guidance of a strict Irish governess at the family residence in [[Park Square, London|Park Square]] which later became the site for [[The Prince's Trust]].<ref name=Anderson2010>{{Cite journal|last=Anderson|first=Robert H.|date=15 April 2010|title=The paediatric cardiology Hall of Fame \u2013 Jane Somerville|journal=Cardiology in the Young|volume=20|issue=3|pages=233\u2013241|doi=10.1017/S1047951110000399|issn=1047-9511}}{{subscription required}}</ref>\n\nDuring the Second World War and [[The Blitz]], when children were ordered out of London, Somerville was sent to a boys [[Preparatory school (United Kingdom)|preparatory school]] in the Welsh village of [[Portmeirion]]. She remained there for three years, being only one of six girls among 70 boys.<ref name=Anderson2010/>\n\nFollowing studies in the sciences at [[Queen's College, London|Queen's College]] school, [[Harley Street]], London, Somerville gained admission into the male dominated [[King's College London GKT School of Medical Education|Guy's Hospital Medical School]], where women medical students had been present for only the previous two years and the class was more than 90% men. During her student years, she was influenced by a visit to the school by [[Alfred Blalock]] of [[Johns Hopkins Hospital]], whose achievements in treating [[tetralogy of Fallot]] with the [[Blalock Taussig shunt]], transformed the lives of children. The once fatal heart disease could now be corrected and turn a blue baby to pink in minutes.<ref name=Warness2008/>\n\n== Early medical career==\n[[File:National Heart Hospital, Westmoreland Street, W1. Wellcome S0007606.jpg|thumb|National Heart Hospital, Westmoreland Street<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wellcomecollection.org/works|title=Catalogue search|website=Wellcome Collection|access-date=7 March 2019}}</ref>]]\nSomerville initially aimed for a career in heart surgery and worked for heart surgery pioneer [[Russell Brock|Sir Russell Brock]]. She recognised her own lack of dexterity and later recounted \"but I was no good because my hands were not connected to my head\"<ref name=Malta/> and changed course to become a cardiologist.<ref name=Warness2008/> She became the first female medical registrar at Guy's Hospital.<ref name=\"BHF\" />\n\nIn 1958, she became a registrar at the [[University College Hospital at Westmoreland Street|National Heart Hospital]] where cardiologist [[Paul Hamilton Wood|Paul Wood]] took her on to his team. Here, her interest in congenital heart disease led her to take on simultaneous work at the [[Great Ormond Street Hospital|Hospital for Sick Children in Great Ormond Street]], London, and she learnt about diseases in babies and surgery with [[Richard Bonham Carter]] and [[David James Waterston|David Waterston]].<ref name=Warness2008/>\n\nIn 1967, during a time of significant innovations in heart surgery, Somerville was appointed as a consultant at the National Heart Hospital. She recognised the unmet need of the increasing number of adolescents and adults who were now surviving the heart conditions they were born with, thus founding the concept of GUCH.<ref name=Warness2008/><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=WOsAblcg0GEC&pg=PA14&dq=jane+somerville+heart#v=onepage&q=jane%20somerville%20heart&f=false|title=Adult Congenital Heart Disease: A Practical Guide|last=Gatzoulis|first=Michael A.|last2=Swan|first2=Lorna|last3=Therrien|first3=Judith|last4=Pantely|first4=George A.|date=2008|publisher=Blackwell Publishing|isbn=978-0-7279-1668-6|location=|pages=14|language=en}}</ref> This new group of survivors had new medical problems and some soon required repeat operations, challenging the cardiologists of the time.<ref name=Warness2008/>\n\nSomerville also worked alongside cardio-thoracic surgeon [[Donald Ross (surgeon)|Donald Ross]], who chose her to be the cardiologist for the first [[heart transplantation]] in the UK in 1968.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thesf.org.uk/50th-anniversary-of-the-first-heart-transplant/|title=The Somerville Foundation 50th Anniversary of the first Heart Transplant|last=Admin|first=Somerville|date=14 October 2018|publisher=The Somerville Foundation|access-date=5 March 2019}}</ref> They co-authored a number of innovative articles, including in 1966, the first report of the use of a homograft [[aortic valve]] to repair [[pulmonary atresia]].<ref name=Warness2008/><ref name=\"witness\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.histmodbiomed.org/sites/default/files/44825.pdf|title=Early heart transplant surgery in the UK {{!}} The History of Modern Biomedicine|last=Tansey|first=Tilli|last2=Reynolds|first2=L. A.|website=www.histmodbiomed.org|page=16|access-date=5 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Later medical career==\n===Paul Wood ward===\nIn 1975, Somerville, \"always feisty and prepared for battle\",<ref name=Warness2008/> succeeded in raising enough funds to open the world's first hospital ward solely for the use of children and adolescents with congenital heart disease. It was named the Paul Wood Ward.<ref name=Warness2008/> The atmosphere differed from a purely children's ward. While it did have a children's play area, guided by a play leader, it also had a kitchen for adolescents and families. Family members could interact with each other, have a coffee and make a snack. This was appreciated by older adolescents, who in turn supported younger ones.<ref name=Warness2008/>\n\n===World Congress===\nIn 1980, she held the first World Congress of Paediatric Cardiology in London, a concept she envisaged.<ref name=Warness2008/> In 1988, she enlisted the help of American heart surgeon [[John W. Kirklin]] during the first Paediatric Cardiac Surgical Congress in [[Bergamo]], resulting in a collaboration between heart physicians and heart surgeons.<ref name=Anderson2010/><ref name=Warness2008/>\n\nSomerville's pioneering GUCH care and teaching led her to be followed by \"Unicorns\",<ref name=\"BHF\">{{Cite web|url=https://blog.bhf.org.uk/professor-jane-somerville-pioneer-of-adult-congenital-heart-disease-care-112846443617|title=Professor Jane Somerville \u2013 pioneer of adult congenital heart disease care|last=Sudlow|first=Charlie|date=1 March 2019|publisher=British Heart Foundation|access-date=11 March 2019}}</ref> her ex-trainees who gather at the World Congress of Paediatric Cardiology every year to celebrate her life and work.<ref name=Warness2008/><ref name=achaheart>{{Cite web|url=https://www.achaheart.org/about-us/people/medical-advisory-board/|title=Medical Advisory Board|website=ACHA|access-date=11 March 2019}}</ref> In explaining the \"Unicorns\", Somerville answered;\n\n<blockquote>I try to teach my fellows that they have to have imagination. You have to be able to diagnose a disease that you have never seen, or perhaps even read about, and you have to combine your memory with it. That's why my trainees are called unicorns, because I used to tell them that there's this imaginary animal that nobody had ever seen but if you saw one in the ward, you\u2019d recognize it. Without the ability to imagine, I\u2019m not sure you would quite know what was going on.<ref name=AAEL2016>{{Cite web|url=https://www.acc.org/latest-in-cardiology/articles/2016/11/30/14/22/accel|title=ACCEL {{!}} American College of Cardiology Extended Learning|website=American College of Cardiology|access-date=23 March 2019}}</ref></blockquote>\n\n===Brompton Hospital===\nThe Brompton Hospital incorporated the National Heart Hospital in 1989, however the adolescent ward was not included in the transition. Somerville thereafter worked on re-establishing one, which was later renamed the Jane Somerville GUCH Unit in 1996.<ref name=Warness2008/>\n\nIn 1995, the British Cardiac Society held the first Paul Wood lecture, which Somerville gave. The title of her speech was \"The Master's Legacy\".<ref name=Warness2008/>\n\nIn 1998, Somerville was appointed emeritus professor of cardiology, Imperial College. She retired a year later.<ref name=Warness2008/>\n\n===GUCH Patients Association ===\nIn the early 1990s, she founded the [[European Society of Cardiology]] Working Group on GUCH and became its chairperson in 1995. The GUCH patients were presenting with numerous problems outside their medical need that she founded and became president of the GUCH patient association in 1994, launched from the now Royal Brompton Hospital. GUCH patients could now talk to each other, seek help for all the social problems and meet to find they were not alone. The organisation was supported by the [[British Heart Foundation]] and its name was subsequently changed to the Somerville Foundation in her honour.<ref name=Anderson2010/><ref name=Warness2008/>\n\n==Awards and honours==\nSomerville is the recipient of the Gold Medal of the [[European Society of Cardiology]], the Guys treasurers Gold Medal in clinical surgery and the Distinguished Service Award of the [[American College of Cardiology]].<ref name=Anderson2010/>\n\nIn 2012, Somerville was named as one of five legends in cardiology at the American College of Cardiology Scientific Sessions.<ref name=ACCSESSION2012>{{Cite web|url=https://www.healio.com/cardiology/news/print/cardiology-today/%7be6b875c2-0fb8-41fd-9bac-f7ba05cff5de%7d/legends-honored-at-2012-acc-scientific-sessions|title='Legends' honored at 2012 ACC Scientific Sessions|date=May 2012|website=healio.com|access-date=23 March 2019}}</ref> A \"self-proclaimed trouble maker\", she shared the event at Chicago with Eugene Braunwald, [[Valentin Fuster]], Antonio Colombo and [[Magdi Yacoub]], when she spoke about her 50 years with heart surgeons.<ref name=Lewis2012>{{Cite web|url=http://archive.constantcontact.com/fs093/1102399426198/archive/1109710331876.html|title=ACC \u2013 Oregon April 2012 News|last=Lewis|first=Sandy|date=April 2012|website=archive.constantcontact.com|access-date=26 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nShe is the second woman, after [[Helen Taussig]], to enter the Paediatric Cardiology Hall of Fame.<ref name=Anderson2010/>\n\n==Personal life==\n[[File:Jane Somerville.jpg|thumb|Jane Somerville, roof garden (2019)]]\nIn 1957, Platnauer married [[Walter Somerville]], who she met in the late 1940s, when she was age 16 and he was staying next door.<ref name=Anderson2010/><ref name=Warness2008/> The couple had four children; one daughter and three sons .<ref name=\"Who's Who 2015\">{{cite web|title=Somerville, Prof. Jane|url=http://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/article/oupww/whoswho/U35635|website=Who's Who 2015|publisher=A & C Black|accessdate=24 January 2015|date=October 2014}}</ref> Walter died in 2005.<ref name=Richmond2005>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/news/2005/sep/17/guardianobituaries|title=Obituary: Walter Somerville|last=Richmond|first=Caroline|date=17 September 2005|work=The Guardian|access-date=5 March 2019|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\nHer hobbies include collecting antiques, roof gardening and opera.<ref name=Warness2008/>\n\n==Retirement==\nFollowing retirement, Somerville continued to travel the world and teach.<ref name=Warness2008/> The GUCH clinic at the [[Mater Dei Hospital]] in Malta is based on her model.<ref name=\"Malta\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20081217/local/cardiologists-explore-possible-purchase-of-mri-machine.237543|title=Cardiologists explore possible purchase of MRI machine|last=Busuttil|first=Cynthia|date=17 December 2008|website=The Times|location=Malta|access-date=22 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013 Somerville was a guest on the BBC's ''[[Desert Island Discs]]'' with [[Kirsty Young]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.histmodbiomed.org/blog/dr-jane-somerville-bbc-radio-4s-desert-island-disks.html|title=Dr Jane Somerville on BBC Radio 4's 'Desert Island Disks' {{!}} The History of Modern Biomedicine|website=www.histmodbiomed.org|access-date=5 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Selected publications==\n*{{cite journal | pmid =  14284359 | doi=10.1136/hrt.27.3.413 | volume=27 | title=OSTIUM PRIMUM DEFECT: FACTORS CAUSING DETERIORATION IN THE NATURAL HISTORY | pmc=503324 | year=1965 | journal=Br Heart J | pages=413\u20139  | last1 = Somerville | first1 = J}}\n*{{cite journal | doi = 10.1016/S0140-6736(66)90600-3 | volume=288 | title=CORRECTION OF PULMONARY ATRESIA WITH A HOMOGRAFT AORTIC VALVE | year=1966 | journal=The Lancet | pages=1446\u20131447 | last1 = Ross | first1 = D}}\n* {{cite journal | pmid = 4194361 | doi=10.1016/s0140-6736(70)91329-2 | volume=2 | title=Surgical correction of Ebstein's anomaly | year=1970 | journal=Lancet | pages=280\u20134  | last1 = Ross | first1 = D | last2 = Somerville | first2 = J}}\n*{{cite journal | pmid = 5470046 | doi=10.1136/hrt.32.5.641 | volume=32 | title=Management of pulmonary atresia | pmc=487386 | year=1970 | journal=Br Heart J | pages=641\u201351  | last1 = Somerville | first1 = J}}\n*{{cite journal | pmid = 154911 | doi=10.1136/hrt.41.1.1 | volume=41 | title=Congenital heart disease--changes in form and function | pmc=482007 | year=1979 | journal=Br Heart J | pages=1\u201322  | last1 = Somerville | first1 = J}}\n*{{cite journal | pmc = 1728862 | pmid=10065034 | doi=10.1136/hrt.80.6.612 | volume=80 | title=Paul Wood Lecture. The master's legacy: the first Paul Wood Lecture | year=1998 | journal=Heart | pages=612-8; discussion 618-9  | last1 = Somerville | first1 = J}}\n*{{cite journal | pmid = 12181200 | doi=10.1136/heart.88.suppl_1.i1 | volume=88 Suppl 1 | title=Grown-up congenital heart (GUCH) disease: current needs and provision of service for adolescents and adults with congenital heart disease in the UK | pmc=1876264 | year=2002 | journal=Heart | pages=i1-14 }}\n*{{cite journal | doi = 10.1017/S1047951112002119 | volume=22 | title=The World Congress of Paediatric Cardiology and Cardiac Surgery: a short factual history by Jane Somerville | year=2012 | journal=Cardiology in the Young | pages=633\u2013638 | last1 = Somerville | first1 = Jane}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*[http://www.onlinejacc.org/content/18/2/315 \"Medical Centre Experiences\"], ''[[Journal of the American College of Cardiology]]'', Volume 18, Issue 2, August 1991, {{DOI|10.1016/0735-1097(91)90570-Y}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uB4EEG20J84 Dr. Somerville- Legends of CV Medicine] (2012)\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4lxmgzPKKZU WSPCHS \u2013 Interview with Dr. Jane Somerville (Intro)] (2016)\n*[https://thesf.org.uk The Somerville Foundation]\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QmrUOK2dhO0 Jane Somerville \u2013 Life and times of leading cardiologists with Rob Califf]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Somerville, Jane}}\n[[Category:1933 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Kensington]]\n[[Category:People educated at Queen's College, London]]\n[[Category:English women medical doctors]]\n[[Category:Academics of Imperial College London]]\n[[Category:British cardiologists]]\n[[Category:Women cardiologists]]\n[[Category:History of heart surgery]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{EngvarB|date=February 2020}}\n{{short description|British physician}}\n{{Infobox medical person\n| honorific_prefix  = \n| name              = Jane Somerville\n| honorific_suffix  = \n| image             = Jane Somerville, library.jpg\n| image_size        = \n| alt               = \n| caption           = Jane Somerville in her personal library (2019)\n| birth_name        = Jane Platnauer\n| birth_date        = {{birth date and age|df=y|24 January 1933}}\n| birth_place       = \n| death_date        = <!-- {{Death date and age|df=y|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date)  -->\n| death_place       = \n| death_cause       = \n| nationality       = British\n| citizenship       = \n| education         = *[[Queen's College, London]]\n*[[King's College London GKT School of Medical Education|Guy's Hospital Medical School]] \n| occupation        = \n| years_active      = \n| known_for         = *Physician to Britain's first [[heart transplantation]] (1968)\n*Founding concept of [[GUCH]]\n*Idea of the first World Congress of Paediatric Cardiology\n*Founding the charity \"The Somerville Foundation\"\n| relations         = \n| website           = \n| profession        = Physician\n| field             = [[Cardiology]]\n| work_institutions = *[[University College Hospital at Westmoreland Street|National Heart Hospital]] \n*[[Great Ormond Street Hospital|Hospital for Sick Children in Great Ormond Street]]\n*[[Brompton Hospital]]\n*[[Imperial College]]\n| specialism        = [[Congenital heart defects]]\n| research_field    = \n| notable_works     = \n| prizes            = *Gold Medal of the [[European Society of Cardiology]]\n* Distinguished Service Award of the [[American College of Cardiology]]\n| child             = \n| module2           = \n| signature         = \n}}\n'''Jane Somerville''' (n\u00e9e '''Platnauer'''; 24 January 1933) is a British emeritus professor of [[cardiologist|cardiology]], [[Imperial College]], who is best known for defining the concept and subspecialty of [[GUCH|grown ups with congenital heart disease]] (GUCH) and being chosen as the physician involved with Britain's first [[heart transplantation]] in 1968.\n\nSomerville was educated first at a boys preparatory school in North Wales, then [[Queen's College, London]], and later at [[King's College London GKT School of Medical Education|Guy's Hospital Medical School]]. Initially drawn to surgery, she chose to pursue a career in cardiology at the [[University College Hospital at Westmoreland Street|National Heart Hospital]], [[Great Ormond Street Hospital|Hospital for Sick Children in Great Ormond Street]] and later at the [[Brompton Hospital]].\n\nHer work led to the opening of the world's first dedicated ward for children and adolescents with congenital heart disease, the first World Congress of Paediatric Cardiology in London, and a GUCH charity which was later renamed \"The Somerville Foundation\" in her honour. The medical professionals who she trained and who have come to celebrate and follow her are known as \"Unicorns\".\n\n==Early life and education==\nJane Somerville was born in [[Edwardes Square]], [[Kensington]], London,<ref name=Anderson2010/> on 24 January 1933<ref name=Warness2008>{{Cite journal|last=Warnes|first=Carole A.|date=April 2008|title=Jane Somerville|journal=Clinical Cardiology|volume=31|issue=4|pages=183\u2013184|doi=10.1002/clc.20279|pmid=18404729|pmc=6652976}}</ref> to Joseph Bertram Platnauer, who was a theatre critic for the ''[[Tatler]]'' magazine<ref name=Anderson2010/> and Pearl Ashton who worked on ''[[Vogue (British magazine)|Vogue]]''.<ref name=Warness2008/><ref name=Birthday>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/happy-birthday-professor-jane-somerville-80-zfc7m3pz5pb|title=Happy Birthday: Professor Jane Somerville, 80|date=24 January 2013|work=The Times|access-date=4 March 2019|issn=0140-0460}}</ref> Her early childhood was spent under the guidance of a strict Irish governess at the family residence in [[Park Square, London|Park Square]] which later became the site for [[The Prince's Trust]].<ref name=Anderson2010>{{Cite journal|last=Anderson|first=Robert H.|date=15 April 2010|title=The paediatric cardiology Hall of Fame \u2013 Jane Somerville|journal=Cardiology in the Young|volume=20|issue=3|pages=233\u2013241|doi=10.1017/S1047951110000399|issn=1047-9511}}{{subscription required}}</ref>\n\nDuring the Second World War and [[The Blitz]], when children were ordered out of London, Somerville was sent to a boys [[Preparatory school (United Kingdom)|preparatory school]] in the Welsh village of [[Portmeirion]]. She remained there for three years, being only one of six girls among 70 boys.<ref name=Anderson2010/>\n\nFollowing studies in the sciences at [[Queen's College, London|Queen's College]] school, [[Harley Street]], London, Somerville gained admission into the male dominated [[King's College London GKT School of Medical Education|Guy's Hospital Medical School]], where women medical students had been present for only the previous two years and the class was more than 90% men. During her student years, she was influenced by a visit to the school by [[Alfred Blalock]] of [[Johns Hopkins Hospital]], whose achievements in treating [[tetralogy of Fallot]] with the [[Blalock Taussig shunt]], transformed the lives of children. The once fatal heart disease could now be corrected and turn a blue baby to pink in minutes.<ref name=Warness2008/>\n\n== Early medical career==\n[[File:National Heart Hospital, Westmoreland Street, W1. Wellcome S0007606.jpg|thumb|National Heart Hospital, Westmoreland Street<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wellcomecollection.org/works|title=Catalogue search|website=Wellcome Collection|access-date=7 March 2019}}</ref>]]\nSomerville initially aimed for a career in heart surgery and worked for heart surgery pioneer [[Russell Brock|Sir Russell Brock]]. She recognised her own lack of dexterity and later recounted \"but I was no good because my hands were not connected to my head\"<ref name=Malta/> and changed course to become a cardiologist.<ref name=Warness2008/> She became the first female medical registrar at Guy's Hospital.<ref name=\"BHF\" />\n\nIn 1958, she became a registrar at the [[University College Hospital at Westmoreland Street|National Heart Hospital]] where cardiologist [[Paul Hamilton Wood|Paul Wood]] took her on to his team. Here, her interest in congenital heart disease led her to take on simultaneous work at the [[Great Ormond Street Hospital|Hospital for Sick Children in Great Ormond Street]], London, and she learnt about diseases in babies and surgery with [[Richard Bonham Carter]] and [[David James Waterston|David Waterston]].<ref name=Warness2008/>\n\nIn 1967, during a time of significant innovations in heart surgery, Somerville was appointed as a consultant at the National Heart Hospital. She recognised the unmet need of the increasing number of adolescents and adults who were now surviving the heart conditions they were born with, thus founding the concept of GUCH.<ref name=Warness2008/><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=WOsAblcg0GEC&pg=PA14&dq=jane+somerville+heart#v=onepage&q=jane%20somerville%20heart&f=false|title=Adult Congenital Heart Disease: A Practical Guide|last=Gatzoulis|first=Michael A.|last2=Swan|first2=Lorna|last3=Therrien|first3=Judith|last4=Pantely|first4=George A.|date=2008|publisher=Blackwell Publishing|isbn=978-0-7279-1668-6|location=|pages=14|language=en}}</ref> This new group of survivors had new medical problems and some soon required repeat operations, challenging the cardiologists of the time.<ref name=Warness2008/>\n\nSomerville also worked alongside cardio-thoracic surgeon [[Donald Ross (surgeon)|Donald Ross]], who chose her to be the cardiologist for the first [[heart transplantation]] in the UK in 1968.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thesf.org.uk/50th-anniversary-of-the-first-heart-transplant/|title=The Somerville Foundation 50th Anniversary of the first Heart Transplant|last=Admin|first=Somerville|date=14 October 2018|publisher=The Somerville Foundation|access-date=5 March 2019}}</ref> They co-authored a number of innovative articles, including in 1966, the first report of the use of a homograft [[aortic valve]] to repair [[pulmonary atresia]].<ref name=Warness2008/><ref name=\"witness\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.histmodbiomed.org/sites/default/files/44825.pdf|title=Early heart transplant surgery in the UK {{!}} The History of Modern Biomedicine|last=Tansey|first=Tilli|last2=Reynolds|first2=L. A.|website=www.histmodbiomed.org|page=16|access-date=5 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Later medical career==\n===Paul Wood ward===\nIn 1975, Somerville, \"always feisty and prepared for battle\",<ref name=Warness2008/> succeeded in raising enough funds to open the world's first hospital ward solely for the use of children and adolescents with congenital heart disease. It was named the Paul Wood Ward.<ref name=Warness2008/> The atmosphere differed from a purely children's ward. While it did have a children's play area, guided by a play leader, it also had a kitchen for adolescents and families. Family members could interact with each other, have a coffee and make a snack. This was appreciated by older adolescents, who in turn supported younger ones.<ref name=Warness2008/>\n\n===World Congress===\nIn 1980, she held the first World Congress of Paediatric Cardiology in London, a concept she envisaged.<ref name=Warness2008/> In 1988, she enlisted the help of American heart surgeon [[John W. Kirklin]] during the first Paediatric Cardiac Surgical Congress in [[Bergamo]], resulting in a collaboration between heart physicians and heart surgeons.<ref name=Anderson2010/><ref name=Warness2008/>\n\nSomerville's pioneering GUCH care and teaching led her to be followed by \"Unicorns\",<ref name=\"BHF\">{{Cite web|url=https://blog.bhf.org.uk/professor-jane-somerville-pioneer-of-adult-congenital-heart-disease-care-112846443617|title=Professor Jane Somerville \u2013 pioneer of adult congenital heart disease care|last=Sudlow|first=Charlie|date=1 March 2019|publisher=British Heart Foundation|access-date=11 March 2019}}</ref> her ex-trainees who gather at the World Congress of Paediatric Cardiology every year to celebrate her life and work.<ref name=Warness2008/><ref name=achaheart>{{Cite web|url=https://www.achaheart.org/about-us/people/medical-advisory-board/|title=Medical Advisory Board|website=ACHA|access-date=11 March 2019}}</ref> In explaining the \"Unicorns\", Somerville answered;\n\n<blockquote>I try to teach my fellows that they have to have imagination. You have to be able to diagnose a disease that you have never seen, or perhaps even read about, and you have to combine your memory with it. That's why my trainees are called unicorns, because I used to tell them that there's this imaginary animal that nobody had ever seen but if you saw one in the ward, you\u2019d recognize it. Without the ability to imagine, I\u2019m not sure you would quite know what was going on.<ref name=AAEL2016>{{Cite web|url=https://www.acc.org/latest-in-cardiology/articles/2016/11/30/14/22/accel|title=ACCEL {{!}} American College of Cardiology Extended Learning|website=American College of Cardiology|access-date=23 March 2019}}</ref></blockquote>\n\n===Brompton Hospital===\nThe Brompton Hospital incorporated the National Heart Hospital in 1989, however the adolescent ward was not included in the transition. Somerville thereafter worked on re-establishing one, which was later renamed the Jane Somerville GUCH Unit in 1996.<ref name=Warness2008/>\n\nIn 1995, the British Cardiac Society held the first Paul Wood lecture, which Somerville gave. The title of her speech was \"The Master's Legacy\".<ref name=Warness2008/>\n\nIn 1998, Somerville was appointed emeritus professor of cardiology, Imperial College. She retired a year later.<ref name=Warness2008/>\n\n===GUCH Patients Association ===\nIn the early 1990s, she founded the [[European Society of Cardiology]] Working Group on GUCH and became its chairperson in 1995. The GUCH patients were presenting with numerous problems outside their medical need that she founded and became president of the GUCH patient association in 1994, launched from the now Royal Brompton Hospital. GUCH patients could now talk to each other, seek help for all the social problems and meet to find they were not alone. The organisation was supported by the [[British Heart Foundation]] and its name was subsequently changed to the Somerville Foundation in her honour.<ref name=Anderson2010/><ref name=Warness2008/>\n\n==Awards and honours==\nSomerville is the recipient of the Gold Medal of the [[European Society of Cardiology]], the Guys treasurers Gold Medal in clinical surgery and the Distinguished Service Award of the [[American College of Cardiology]].<ref name=Anderson2010/>\n\nIn 2012, Somerville was named as one of five legends in cardiology at the American College of Cardiology Scientific Sessions.<ref name=ACCSESSION2012>{{Cite web|url=https://www.healio.com/cardiology/news/print/cardiology-today/%7be6b875c2-0fb8-41fd-9bac-f7ba05cff5de%7d/legends-honored-at-2012-acc-scientific-sessions|title='Legends' honored at 2012 ACC Scientific Sessions|date=May 2012|website=healio.com|access-date=23 March 2019}}</ref> A \"self-proclaimed trouble maker\", she shared the event at Chicago with Eugene Braunwald, [[Valentin Fuster]], Antonio Colombo and [[Magdi Yacoub]], when she spoke about her 50 years with heart surgeons.<ref name=Lewis2012>{{Cite web|url=http://archive.constantcontact.com/fs093/1102399426198/archive/1109710331876.html|title=ACC \u2013 Oregon April 2012 News|last=Lewis|first=Sandy|date=April 2012|website=archive.constantcontact.com|access-date=26 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nShe is the second woman, after [[Helen Taussig]], to enter the Paediatric Cardiology Hall of Fame.<ref name=Anderson2010/>\n\n==Personal life==\n[[File:Jane Somerville.jpg|thumb|Jane Somerville, roof garden (2019)]]\nIn 1957, Platnauer married [[Walter Somerville]], who she met in the late 1940s, when she was age 16 and he was staying next door.<ref name=Anderson2010/><ref name=Warness2008/> The couple had four children; one daughter and three sons .<ref name=\"Who's Who 2015\">{{cite web|title=Somerville, Prof. Jane|url=http://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/article/oupww/whoswho/U35635|website=Who's Who 2015|publisher=A & C Black|accessdate=24 January 2015|date=October 2014}}</ref> Walter died in 2005.<ref name=Richmond2005>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/news/2005/sep/17/guardianobituaries|title=Obituary: Walter Somerville|last=Richmond|first=Caroline|date=17 September 2005|work=The Guardian|access-date=5 March 2019|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\nHer hobbies include collecting antiques, roof gardening and opera.<ref name=Warness2008/>\n\n==Retirement==\nFollowing retirement, Somerville continued to travel the world and teach.<ref name=Warness2008/> The GUCH clinic at the [[Mater Dei Hospital]] in Malta is based on her model.<ref name=\"Malta\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20081217/local/cardiologists-explore-possible-purchase-of-mri-machine.237543|title=Cardiologists explore possible purchase of MRI machine|last=Busuttil|first=Cynthia|date=17 December 2008|website=The Times|location=Malta|access-date=22 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013 Somerville was a guest on the BBC's ''[[Desert Island Discs]]'' with [[Kirsty Young]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.histmodbiomed.org/blog/dr-jane-somerville-bbc-radio-4s-desert-island-disks.html|title=Dr Jane Somerville on BBC Radio 4's 'Desert Island Disks' {{!}} The History of Modern Biomedicine|website=www.histmodbiomed.org|access-date=5 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Selected publications==\n*[https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC503324/pdf/brheartj00338-0103.pdf \u201cOstium Primum Defect: Factors Causing Deterioration in the Natural History\u201d], ''British Heart Journal'' 21 August 1964, pp.&nbsp;413\u2013419, {{PMID|14284359}}\n*[https://www.thelancet.com/journals/lancet/article/PIIS0140-6736(66)90600-3/fulltext \"Correction of pulmonary atresia with a homograft aortic valve\"], co-authored with Donald Ross, ''[[The Lancet]]'', 31 December 1966, pp.&nbsp;1446\u20131447. {{Doi|10.1016/S0140-6736(66)90600-3}}\n*[https://www.thelancet.com/journals/lancet/article/PIIS0140-6736(70)91329-2/fulltext \u201cSurgical correction of Ebstein's anomaly\u201d], co-authored with Donald Ross, ''The Lancet'', 8 August 1970, pp.&nbsp;280\u2013284. {{PMID|4194361}}\n*[https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC487386/pdf/brheartj00309-0063.pdf \"Management of pulmonary atresia\"], ''[[British Heart Journal]]'', September 1970, pp.&nbsp;641\u2013651. {{PMID|5470046}}\n*[https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC482007/pdf/brheartj00203-0008.pdf \"Congenital heart disease\u2014changes in form and function\"], ''British Heart Journal'', January 1979, pp.&nbsp;1\u201322. {{PMID|154911}}\n*[https://europepmc.org/backend/ptpmcrender.fcgi?accid=PMC1728862&blobtype=pdf \"The master\u2019s legacy: The first Paul Wood lecture\"], ''Heart'', 1998, pp.&nbsp;612\u2013619.\n*[https://heart.bmj.com/content/heartjnl/88/suppl_1/i1.full.pdf \"Grown-up congenital heart (GUCH) disease: Current needs and provision of service for adolescents and adults with congenital heart disease in the UK], ''[[Heart (journal)|Heart]]'', 2002.\n*[http://eds.a.ebscohost.com.rsm.idm.oclc.org/eds/pdfviewer/pdfviewer?vid=2&sid=cac88ed0-a07c-4e39-8f3f-bfb5849f6d2a%40pdc-v-sessmgr01 \"The World Congress of Paediatric Cardiology and Cardiac Surgery: a short factual history\"], ''Cardiology in the Young'' (2012), pp.&nbsp;633\u2013638, {{doi|10.1017/S1047951112002119}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*[http://www.onlinejacc.org/content/18/2/315 \"Medical Centre Experiences\"], ''[[Journal of the American College of Cardiology]]'', Volume 18, Issue 2, August 1991, {{DOI|10.1016/0735-1097(91)90570-Y}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uB4EEG20J84 Dr. Somerville- Legends of CV Medicine] (2012)\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4lxmgzPKKZU WSPCHS \u2013 Interview with Dr. Jane Somerville (Intro)] (2016)\n*[https://thesf.org.uk The Somerville Foundation]\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QmrUOK2dhO0 Jane Somerville \u2013 Life and times of leading cardiologists with Rob Califf]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Somerville, Jane}}\n[[Category:1933 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Kensington]]\n[[Category:People educated at Queen's College, London]]\n[[Category:English women medical doctors]]\n[[Category:Academics of Imperial College London]]\n[[Category:British cardiologists]]\n[[Category:Women cardiologists]]\n[[Category:History of heart surgery]]\n", "name_user": "Rjwilmsi", "label": "safe", "comment": "Journal cites:,", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jane_Somerville"}
